    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-09-27T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-09-27T08:00:00-05:00" n="99"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d99">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">762.9411/21: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Toyko</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-09-27T22:00:00+09:00"
                            >September 27, 1940—10 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received September 27—2:15 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>909. At 9:45 o’clock tonight we were given by the Foreign Office the following
                    four documents in English translation shortly before their release to the press: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>Summary of the three-power pact between Japan, Germany and Italy
                            signed on September 27, 1940 at Berlin;</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>Radio address by the Minister for Foreign Affairs;</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>Imperial rescript by the Emperor;</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>Message of the Prime Minister.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>In view of the prime importance of these documents in connection with the present
                    critical crisis and being informed that complete texts may not be cabled to the
                    American press, I feel obliged to telegraph documents numbers 2, 3, and 4 in
                    full so that Department may study their tone and substance without delay. The
                    texts follow <pb facs="0231" n="165" xml:id="pg_165"/> in three ensuing
                    telegrams. The summary of the pact<note n="6" xml:id="d99fn6">Summary of pact as
                        transmitted to the Department by the Ambassador in Japan in his despatch No.
                        5038, October 5, 1940, is printed <hi rend="italic">infra</hi>.</note>
                    itself had already been announced on the radio from the United States
                    tonight.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
